WRITING.TITLE: My grandpa was a genius
WRITING.TEXT: I just realized my midwestern farmer grandpa (deceased) who lived to a healthy 94, basically ate "keto" his whole life. He used to put butter on every slab of meat that he ate (and there was a slab at every dinner) and usually had that with a side of vegetables (there were mashed potatoes once in a while, but the ratio of potato to butter and heavy cream was about 1:3). Eggs fried in butter or bacon grease practically every day of his life. Fruit was only occasionally, and usually just berries from the yard. Snacks consisted of nuts that he would shell, then lick and dip in a plate of salt or maybe some radishes and more salt. Dessert was an occasional (and I mean occasional) cookie that he would put some butter on (thought it was weird until he had me try it) or a scoop of full fat ice cream. He didn't drink alcohol...beverages were water, fresh (I guess you'd call it "raw" now) milk, or some sun tea. He drove himself to California from Iowa when he was 90. He was still doing the Sunday crossword until he passed. Never had a heart attack or diabetes. Was never overweight. Had all of his original teeth. Only wore reading glasses. Screw the FDA food pyramid and the damage it has caused.

WRITING.TITLE: Reality
WRITING.TEXT: Just 4 months ago I was still able to convince myself that I wasn't morbidly obese. Sure, I was big (5'10" 275). But I "carried it well" and I looked 30-40lbs lighter than that. However, my wife had stopped telling me I wasn't big. In fact she was beginning to beg me to get healthy. But I had built up a persona of myself that I still felt invincible and that I could do what I wanted health wise, like I could for so much of my life (former hard working hard playing captain badass athlete). Now, 45 pounds lost later, things have reversed. My body image has become realistic again. I realize that the 50 additional pounds that I am still carrying now compared to when I was playing 3 soccer matches a week, running trails for miles just for something to do, throwing weights around that I would get a hernia just looking at now, are actually there. It's not an illusion. Sucking in my gut in when looking in the mirror to coddle my ego is pointless. Still Feeling the strain in my knees (albeit much less than 45 pounds ago) when going up stairs is a symptom of my weight, not due to an old sports injury (only had a minor one in one knee, not both)like I kept convincing myself. I am living in reality now. And it feels amazing. *side note...my wife was thinking I look "skinny" now. Like I was fine where I was. And then I showed her our wedding photo from 12 years ago (this Sunday!) when I was a soft 200 and she gasped. And then I showed her a couple shirtless photos of me a few years before that when I was a rock hard 180. She told me to get my fat ass to the gym so she could get some of that. I love her.

WRITING.TITLE: SV (and NSV) all in one at the doctors office
WRITING.TEXT: Went in for a physical and a couple other things. The nurse checking me in asked me to step on the scale and read the number to her. I did, hopped off, and sat down. Then I proceeded to watch her input data on her computer until she came to what was obviously my weight at my last visit 6 months ago. She did a double take then looked back at the scale and hit the button (it was digital) to confirm the number I had read to her. She let out a low whistle and said..."wow...you've lost some weight!" I had the biggest sh#t eating grin on my face you've ever seen when I said , "yeah...a bit. Still have a little way to go." Down 60 pounds (started keto about 4 1/2 mos ago). Blood pressure (118/68) and heart rate (60) both looking good. Blood drawn and awaiting test results that I'm fairly confident in. I'm a lazy keto-er. But I haven't cheated (more than literally one French fry a couple times) at all. I don't measure or track. I eat meat, veggies, cheese, nuts basically in that order of magnitude. I drink water, sparkling water, coffee, and have recently added in some 0 carb sport drinks. I occasionally have a few bites of halo top or a quest bar. I don't "work out" per se, by as my weight has come off I have become progressively more active. Work like a paid laborer doing yard work on the weekends for 4-6 hours a day. Practice soccer juggling with my daughter 30-60 mins at a time a few times a week. And all around just move more. I feel reborn. I'm lady killer good looking again, I have energy I haven't had in 10 years, I sleep like I'm drugged, I can actually play with my kids (in fact I'm considering working my way up to actually playing soccer again...think I could do it now, but I need some endurance training), my sack time has gotten better for both the wife and I. Life is good and getting better.
